hands_on_practices.solution:
By definition of product measure, for any measurable rectangles $A \times B$ with $A, B \in \mathcal{B}(\mathbb{R})$, the product measure satisfies
$$
\mu(A \times B) = \delta_{a}(A)\,\delta_{b}(B) = \begin{cases}
1 & \text{if } a \in A \text{ and } b \in B, \\
0 & \text{otherwise.}
\end{cases}
$$
Define the Dirac measure at the point $(a,b)$ on $(\mathbb{R}^{2}, \mathcal{B}(\mathbb{R}^{2}))$ by
$$
\delta_{(a,b)}(E) = \begin{cases}
1 & \text{if } (a,b) \in E, \\
0 & \text{if } (a,b) \notin E,
\end{cases}
$$
for every $E \in \mathcal{B}(\mathbb{R}^{2})$. For rectangles $A \times B$, we have
$$
\delta_{(a,b)}(A \times B) = \begin{cases}
1 & \text{if } a \in A \text{ and } b \in B, \\
0 & \text{otherwise,}
\end{cases}
$$
which equals $\delta_{a}(A)\,\delta_{b}(B)$. Thus $\mu$ and $\delta_{(a,b)}$ agree on the $\pi$-system of measurable rectangles, which generates $\mathcal{B}(\mathbb{R}^{2})$. Since both are probability measures, the uniqueness theorem (via the $\pi$-$\lambda$ argument) implies
$$
\mu = \delta_{(a,b)} \quad \text{on } \mathcal{B}(\mathbb{R}^{2}).
$$
Equivalently, for any $E \in \mathcal{B}(\mathbb{R}^{2})$,
$$
\mu(E) = \delta_{(a,b)}(E) = \begin{cases}
1 & \text{if } (a,b) \in E, \\
0 & \text{otherwise.}
\end{cases}
$$
Therefore, the correct characterization among the given options is that $\mu(E)=1$ if $(a,b)\in E$ and $\mu(E)=0$ otherwise, which corresponds to option B.
